<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-517-733  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 517 733.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Oct 15 1990 n612 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'Verdict' in, Intel guilty: arbitrator cites breach of faith iniAPX86 pact. (AMD will collect damages in technology-exchangesuit)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thompson, John; Wirbel, Loring.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Retired Judge Barton Phelps holds Intel Corp ultimatelyresponsible for the failure of a technology-exchange pact withAdvanced Micro Devices (AMD) and found Intel liable for damages toAMD for senior management's decision to frustrate AMD's efforts inthe pact, for failure to transfer the 8087 math coprocessor toAMD, and for failure to transfer updates on various products in atimely and complete manner.andP;  While Phelps does not exclude thepossibility that rights to Intel's 80386 technology could be partof the award, AMD uses the occasion to announce its own version ofthe 386, to be formally introduced as soon as a separate suit overAMD's use of the 386 designation is resolved.andP;  During the reliefphase of the arbitration, scheduled to begin Nov 15, 1990, Phelpswill examine AMD's claim of damages and determine the amount andnature of the settlement.andP;  AMD is seeking more than $500 millionin damages, plus the rights to the 386 chip, but will have to showtangible proof of damage claims.andP;  A spokesman for Intel says thefirm is not afraid of having to transfer rights to the 386 mask,as there is a value-for-value exchange clause in the contract.andO;Further, the spokesman doubts that AMD will be able to prove $500million in quantifiable damages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (cases)Advanced Micro Devices Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    INTC; AMD.andO;Product:   Intel 80386 (Microprocessor) (cases).andO;Topic:     Court CasesLaw SuitTechnology TransferArbitrationMicroprocessors.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>